BC format, the book strikes a unique balance between the practical and the theoretical: the analysis is backed up by lived experience, the arguments are rooted in concrete examples and there are suggestions for constructive action. Roughly half of the entries expose the structural underpinnings of projects and circulation, isolating traits such as opportunism, neoliberalism, inequality, fear and cynicism at the root of the condition of the projectariat. This discussion is paired with a practical account of different modes of action, such as art strikes, productive withdrawals, political struggles and better social time machines. Just as proletarians had nothing to lose but their chains, the projectarians have nothing to miss but their deadlines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtxEconomic aspects. 0aArtxVocational guidance. 0aPrecarious employment. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Labor.2bisacsh  aNGOs.  aart workers.  acontemporary art.  aculture industry.  acuratorship.  afreelancing.  agalleries.  aneoliberalism.  aprecarity.  aprojectariat.1 aSzreder, Kuba, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616134540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526161345423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526161345/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles